name: GraphiQL & GraphQL LSP Ecosystem
description:
GraphiQL is the GraphQL Language Tooling Reference Ecosystem, intended for building both browser & desktop IDE tools for writing schemas & executing operations in the GraphQL Language. 

This monorepo contains:
 
- a full-service, run-anywhere LSP (langserver.org) service
- monaco editor mode
- codemirror mode
- lsp server library
- command line LSP server
- fully extensible web implementation of the monaco mode
contribution_justification: Non-trivial contribution file in repository: <https://github.com/graphql/graphiql/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md>.
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/graphql/graphiql/blob/master/LICENSE>.
floss_license_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification:
// No appropriate folder found for documentation basics.

There is a root readme that leads you to the subpackage readme files. GraphiQL subpackage itself having the most extensive documentation, and other documentation focused more at the interface levels.
documentation_interface_justification:
These are documented in:
packages/graphiql/README.md
packages/graphql-language-service-server/README.md
packages/graphql-language-service/README.md

these are the interfaces we currently intend for public consumption, though the codemirror mode and brand new monaco mode need some improvement for API reference docs

also, we were building an automated API typedoc up until a build issue ~1week ago but we've already prioritized a fix that will improve build times.
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: For example, all subpackages are currently in pre-release state (alpha). our usual flow is to re-release end-user packages and dependents as pre-releases for ~week, and if no further bug reports, we go live. automated tests give assurance, but we still spend lots of time testing pre-releases, and even more time manually testing pre-releases before graduating to stable again. for example, some packages in alpha now will be in beta within a few weeks, others will be stable. independent versioning is what we call this
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: semver with prerelease alpha, beta, rc
version_tags_justification: tags for each release of every subpackage
release_notes_justification:
- https://github.com/graphql/graphiql/blob/master/packages/graphiql/CHANGELOG.md
- https://github.com/graphql/graphiql/blob/master/packages/codemirror-graphql/CHANGELOG.md
- https://github.com/graphql/graphiql/blob/master/packages/graphiql/CHANGELOG.md
... etc for each package

also, see: github releases!
release_notes_vulns_justification: dependabot is configured to only issue immediate security PRs, and uses a conventional commits standard that ensures it is automatically logged as a security fix in our changelog and contains a link to the CVE
enhancement_responses_justification: we are in a feature freeze state as we rewrite the core for a new major version API. all new features are being deferred to plugin proposals.
report_archive_justification:
https://github.com/graphql/graphiql/issues
also our discord has unlimited history (for support)
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: haven't had this issue yet. have fixed dependency CVEs but have not had any direct vulns yet :crosses fingers:
build_justification: typescript project references, babel and webpack!
test_most_justification: we're at ~60% coverage and in the midst of a rewrite, but 100% test coverage is the goal for the next beta as we progress through the rebuild. this figure is also not counting our small but critical e2e suite, couldn't figure out how to get cypress talking to istanbul
tests_are_added_justification: in the midst of a rewrite, so we plan on rewriting most of the test suite as the API stabilizes.
warnings_fixed_justification: CI builds rejected for eslint or formatting failures
know_secure_design_justification: I have designed multiple systems audited by US federal govt, passed multiple third party HIPAA audits with flying colors, etc.
know_common_errors_justification:
- npm dependency errors that are user facing
- common browser security explots
crypto_published_justification: no plans to implement any cryptography beside our lets encrypt SSL certificates on netlify. that is up to the user implementation.
delivery_mitm_justification: users are not required to use https for their own service development purposes
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: both github and dependabot help us with this. dependabot opens PRs to fix CVEs on day 0 as public PRs, and i usually merge them within a few hours. i would never publish with known vulnerabilities
static_analysis_justification: eslint! for javascript and typescript. and prettier. dependabot scans us but is not floss. we link to snyk's report that they automatically generate for us from a badge on our root readme. no tools like sonarqube yet.
dynamic_analysis_justification: does cypress count? or do you mean dynamic security analysis like OWASP?
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Our core typescript (runs as javascript, obv.) libraries are designed to run in multiple runtimes, and in each case, using this compiled javascript output is memory unsafe at a low level. For example, GraphiQL can and is run inside electron runtime, vscode runtime, and of course browser runtimes, each introducing memory management threats. Also, despite the default nature of node.js or browser main thread, he new monaco mode introduces multiple web worker threads, and the lsp server process runs for each graphql tab in vscode, etc. That said, I'm embarassed to admit I've never encountered the idea of using automated tools to detect memory safety. Is this something I should add as, say, a daily github action? or at least a pre-release step?
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: no dynamic security analysis going on. does snyk's runtime dependency vulnerability scanning count, or do we need owasp/etc too?
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: switched from jenkins to github actions and its flyin'! netlify deploy previews are a bit slow but very very important, esp with a lack of 100% coverage, but even if we did. this is why manual regression tests are and will always be a part of every stable release.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification:
for a moment we leaked our codecov token and thats it
we disabled CI publishing for this reason. publish events are only issued from my local Linux laptop using MFA over npm auth v2
english_justification: do we need issue templates in english to satisfy this?
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.

name: preCICE
description:
preCICE (Precise Code Interaction Coupling Environment) is a coupling library for partitioned multi-physics simulations, including, but not restricted to fluid-structure interaction and conjugate heat transfer simulations. Partitioned means that preCICE couples existing programs (solvers) capable of simulating a subpart of the complete physics involved in a simulation. This allows for the high flexibility that is needed to keep a decent time-to-solution for complex multi-physics scenarios. preCICE runs efficiently on a wide spectrum of systems, from low-end workstations up to complete compute clusters and has proven scalability on 10000s of MPI Ranks.

The software offers methods for transient equation coupling, communication means, and data mapping schemes. preCICE is written in C++ and offers additional bindings for C, Fortran, Matlab, and Python. Ready-to-use adapters for well-known commercial and open-source solvers, such as OpenFOAM, deal.II, FEniCS, SU2, or CalculiX, are available. Due to the minimally-invasive approach of preCICE, adapters for in-house codes can be implemented and validated in only a few weeks.

version_semver_justification:
The versions are unique in 0.x.0 manner.
SemVer is not used probably from historic reasons.
Versioning is not that important as PKCS#11 API is stable and driven by different versioning than we have. The libopensc is not considered public API.
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/blob/master/NEWS>.
release_notes_vulns_justification: Latest release lists all publicly known vulnerabilities: https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/releases/tag/0.20.0
report_tracker_justification: Github issues are used for tracking issues: https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/issues
report_responses_justification: Frequently reviewing the new issues. Most of them have comments during first 24 hours.
enhancement_responses_justification: We respond, but it is not possible to fix support for all cards we do not have.
report_archive_justification:
Github provides archive for issues. There are just few issues without any comment, mostly from project members or based on previous discussions:
https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+sort%3Acomments-asc
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: Most of the recent reports come from oss-fuzz and they are fixed in their time. To previously externally reported vulnerabilities we answered in 14 days.
test_justification:
Few integration tests for tools: https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/tree/master/tests
Few unit tests: https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/tree/master/src/tests/unittests
Testsuite: https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/tree/master/src/tests/p11test
test_invocation_justification: "make check" runs both unit and integration tests if all dependencies are available
test_most_justification:
very large code base and poor testing history makes this hard to achieve. 

Current project members do not have all supported smart cards for testing and it is hard to say if the cards are still in use.
test_policy_justification:
it is probably not ok, but automating tests against real hardware is hard, but we are trying to codify this.

https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/wiki/Getting-involved-in-OpenSC-development
tests_are_added_justification:
Many recent contributions try to improve the test coverage:
https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/pull/1960
https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/pull/2015
https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/pull/1830
warnings_justification:
-Werror is used by default from configure (--enable-strict):
https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/blob/master/configure.ac#L152
https://github.com/OpenSC/OpenSC/blob/master/configure.ac#L1078
warnings_fixed_justification: CI runs with -Werror, which is reviewed with every PR and merge.
crypto_keylength_justification: opensc is not a policy library -- either the hardware or the application should decide what key sizes it should use.
crypto_random_justification: I see usages of openssl's RAND_bytes(), which is secure.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: all oss-fuzz issues reported are fixed in 60 days
static_analysis_justification: coverity is running periodically, lgtm runs in CI
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: coverity is running periodically, lgtm runs in CI
static_analysis_fixed_justification: as above, all of the issues from oss-fuzz are handled.
static_analysis_often_justification: coverity runs on every commit merged to master.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Fuzzers using oss-fuzz are implemented and continuously running.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
Travis runs tests against existing virtual/emulated cards, Gitlab CI runs tests against real cards in mirror [1]
[1] https://gitlab.com/redhat-crypto/OpenSC/pipelines

no_leaked_credentials_justification: the secrets used in CI are encrypted
